</p><div class=3D"paywall-jump" data-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div>=
<p><span>A while back I caught up with a guy from my high school graduating=
 class. After we graduated from high school, he spent a few years flounderi=
ng in community college. Failed half his classes, smoked a lot of weed in p=
arking lots, hooked up with random girls. This is =E2=80=9CJohn,=E2=80=9D f=
or those of you who read </span><a href=3D"https://a.co/d/00QqpQM" rel=3D""=
>my memoir </a><em><a href=3D"https://a.co/d/00QqpQM" rel=3D"">Troubled</a>=
</em><span>. </span></p><p>He joined the military at age 23. He said it was=
 tough, but he enjoyed the challenge. Lost a bunch of weight, felt good abo=
ut himself, and exited with a plan to finish college.</p><p>Honorably disch=
arged. Then fell back into old habits. Back to the wake-and-bake life, ditc=
hing classes, gained weight. The external pressure was off, and he went bac=
k to his old ways. Not quite on the same level as before. Slackers in their=
 30s can=E2=80=99t compete with their 19-year-old selves at being a delinqu=
ent. But he had become roughly the same guy again.</p><p>I thought about th=
is while listening to the behavioral geneticist Kathryn Paige Harden on the=
 Sam Harris podcast.</p><p>At one point in the conversation, they were disc=
ussing the role of IQ in life outcomes. A paraphrased quote from Harden:</p=
><blockquote><p><em>=E2=80=9CWhat are we actually aiming for=E2=80=94higher=
 IQs, more education? Or are we aiming for people to be healthy and happy? =
A society where you don=E2=80=99t need to be especially talented or educate=
d to get decent healthcare and live a good life.=E2=80=9D</em></p></blockqu=
ote><p>This is perfectly stated. The chattering classes are obsessed with e=
ducation. I can=E2=80=99t open a prestige media webpage, liberal or conserv=
ative, without seeing at least one headline that has something to do with c=
ollege or the education system.</p><p><span>Americans are preoccupied with =
college, so much that </span><a href=3D"https://www.theclassroom.com/percen=
tage-high-school-students-attend-college-after-graduation-1423.html" rel=3D=
"">more than half</a><span> of high school graduates enroll in college. The=
n nearly </span><a href=3D"https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/10/bill-gates-us-co=
llege-dropout-rates-are-tragic.html" rel=3D"">half of them drop out</a><spa=
n>, often saddled with debt. College is the ticket to a good life, we=E2=80=
=99re told. Get that degree, land a white-collar job, and happiness awaits.=
</span></p><p>A smaller contingent of people focus more on IQ, and how this=
, rather than education level, is the more important factor for outcomes li=
ke income, marriage, obesity, life expectancy, etc. They point out research=
 showing that education doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have much of an effect on l=
ifting IQ scores.</p><p><span>For example, this </span><a href=3D"https://w=
ww.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0160289618302198" rel=3D"">st=
udy</a><span> shows that verbal IQ has declined among college graduates sin=
ce the 1970s Perhaps because more people are going to college now than in t=
he past. More recently, a recent meta-analysis </span><a href=3D"https://ww=
w.researchgate.net/publication/372338962_Average_university_students'_IQ_is=
_no_longer_above_average_but_merely_average" rel=3D"">found</a><span> that =
the average intelligence of university students and university graduates ha=
s dropped to the average of the general population. Though as I=E2=80=99ve =
noted before, </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/nobody-is-a=
-prisoner-of-their-iq?utm_source=3Dpublication-search" rel=3D"">no one is a=
 prisoner of their IQ</a><span>. </span></p><p>Either way, we are focused o=
n the wrong thing. Why should college or smarts or conscientiousness be req=
uired to live a fulfilling life? </p><div><hr></div><p><span>Families have =
crumbled and it is rarely discussed as a factor in social changes. This col=
lapse is primarily concentrated among the poor and working class. Dr. Drew =
and Adam Carolla in a recent interview </span><a href=3D"https://twitter.co=
m/Elex_Michaelson/status/1281991534485729283?s=3D20" rel=3D"">said</a><span=
>, =E2=80=9Cfar too many people come from broken families and it is hardly =
ever addressed by the media or politicians. Whenever someone says we need t=
o have an 'honest conversation'...that's the conversation we need to have.=
=E2=80=9D</span></p><p><span>As Charles Murray has </span><a href=3D"https:=
//amzn.to/2CsZeZB" rel=3D"">documented</a><span>, this phenomenon can be ob=
served through the lens of social class. =E2=80=9CBelmont=E2=80=9D is short=
hand for the top 20% of Americans, =E2=80=9CFishtown=E2=80=9D is the bottom=
 30%.</span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container"><figure><a class=
