worked at a pizza joint when I was a teenager. Most of my coworkers were in=
 their twenties, some in their thirties. My manager was in his forties, and=
 had spent some time in prison.</p><p>They weren=E2=80=99t bad people. Some=
 were more reliable and honest than anyone else I=E2=80=99d ever meet. But =
they weren=E2=80=99t going to college. They weren=E2=80=99t going to land a=
n interesting and lucrative job in our small California town. And they had =
no desire to leave.</p><p><span>It=E2=80=99s hard for many people to </span=
><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/it-would-seem-that-some-sociall=
y" rel=3D"">accept this</a><span>. Most people are not exceptionally brilli=
ant, or strikingly attractive, creative, athletic, musical, etc. Most peopl=
e are perfectly average. One goal of a decent society is to ensure that suc=
h people can live with dignity and feel valued in their community, regardle=
ss of their endowments. Social guardrails used to help with this. Maybe the=
 absence of guardrails=E2=80=94unrestrained freedom=E2=80=94can work if you=
're a very smart young person from an upper-middle-class family and there a=
ren't a lot of opportunities around you for your life to go in a catastroph=
ic direction. But if you're a teenager in a place like Red Bluff or in othe=
r rundown parts of the country, unconstrained freedom will just give you op=
portunities for your life to unravel.</span></p><div class=3D"subscription-=
